00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:25.640
So where were we last time?

00:00:25.640 --> 00:00:28.480
So we had derived the
Fermion Lagrangian

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:30.460
which is at the
top of the board,

00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:32.320
and really the only
difference between this

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:36.280
and what we talked about earlier
is that we had to perform

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:37.550
the multipole expansion.

00:00:37.550 --> 00:00:41.110
So we distinguish between
collinear momenta that

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:43.690
are scaling like a collinear
momentum and momentum that

00:00:43.690 --> 00:00:47.260
are scaling like an ultrasoft,
and only the collinear pieces

00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:49.810
were showing up in here, and
same with the collinear gauge

00:00:49.810 --> 00:00:50.310
field.

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:53.470
It was only showing up in here,
whereas both were showing up

00:00:53.470 --> 00:00:55.210
in here.

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:57.220
There's only a single
type of derivative

00:00:57.220 --> 00:00:59.740
here, because
ultrasoft and collinear

00:00:59.740 --> 00:01:01.900
momenta are the same size
in the end component.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:03.900
But they're different in
these other components,

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:06.820
so we had these labels
in this label operator

00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:08.845
that picked out the
collinear momenta.

00:01:08.845 --> 00:01:10.970
So we could define collinear
covariate derivatives,

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:12.790
if you like, with
this subscript n,

00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:15.610
whereas this D is like a
full derivative that involves

00:01:15.610 --> 00:01:18.580
both types of gauge field.

00:01:18.580 --> 00:01:20.830
And then at the end of
lecture, it was kind of rushed,

00:01:20.830 --> 00:01:23.653
but I was talking about the
collinear gluon Lagrangian,

00:01:23.653 --> 00:01:25.570
and I said there is a
set of replacement rules

00:01:25.570 --> 00:01:28.690
that we could make to
effectively do the same thing

00:01:28.690 --> 00:01:29.668
that we did here.

00:01:29.668 --> 00:01:31.210
And now I've just
written out for you

00:01:31.210 --> 00:01:34.690
with that Lagrangian is with
those replacement rules.

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:39.940
So curly D is basically just
taking all the derivatives

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:41.650
and taking only the
leading order pieces.

00:01:41.650 --> 00:01:44.210
So we take the collinear
pieces in this component

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:45.490
and this component.

00:01:45.490 --> 00:01:48.380
We take the ultrasoft
pieces in this component.

00:01:48.380 --> 00:01:50.650
And then if you wrote
the original Lagrangian

00:01:50.650 --> 00:01:52.690
as a commutator of two
covariant derivatives,

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:54.860
you'd just replace it by
the leading order pieces,

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:57.580
and that's what the leading
order action will be.

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:00.130
Then, we had to think
about gauge fixing.

00:02:00.130 --> 00:02:02.830
Since this is the
collinear gluon Lagrangian,

00:02:02.830 --> 00:02:05.410
we should think about
collinear gauge fixing.

00:02:05.410 --> 00:02:07.270
This here as a general
covariant gauge

00:02:07.270 --> 00:02:09.610
fixing with parameter
tau, and then there's

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:11.470
a corresponding ghost term.

00:02:11.470 --> 00:02:14.800
And in this Lagrangian, the
usual way it would look,

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:20.740
this would be i
partial, and then

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:24.850
I said that, because we don't
want the collinear gauge fixing

00:02:24.850 --> 00:02:27.910
term to break ultrasoft
gauge invariance,

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:29.710
we're going to turn
that i partial into

00:02:29.710 --> 00:02:31.321
a covariant derivative under--

00:02:34.217 --> 00:02:35.800
we're going to include
this piece here

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:40.150
at the n dot a ultrasoft
to make it ultrasoft gauge

00:02:40.150 --> 00:02:41.550
invariant at lowest order.

00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:42.050
OK?

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:44.200
So that's really the only--

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:47.800
other than just doing this most
naive thing by just replacing

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:49.450
derivatives by
covariant derivatives,

00:02:49.450 --> 00:02:51.250
and you might think,
well, I'll just keep

00:02:51.250 --> 00:02:52.458
this as a partial derivative.

00:02:52.458 --> 00:02:54.190
Since it's to
doing gauge fixing,

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:56.140
I don't need to
make it covariant,

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:59.110
but we do want to make it
covariant under the ultrasofts,

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:04.690
and that's why I write
this curly D ultrasoft.

00:03:04.690 --> 00:03:05.190
OK.

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:08.580
So that gives you the
leading order Lagrangian.

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:12.180
Once you put together
this with what

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:13.680
you want for the
ultrasoft, then you

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:16.650
would have the full
leading order Lagrangian,

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:18.780
and the ultrasoft part
is actually very simple.

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:26.430
So for the ultrasoft
part, we just

00:03:26.430 --> 00:03:29.830
take a full QCD action
for the ultrasoft field.

00:03:29.830 --> 00:03:35.085
So this is just
q ultrasoft bar i

00:03:35.085 --> 00:03:39.000
D slash ultrasoft q ultrasoft.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:46.350
And likewise for the gluon
piece, it's just QCD,

00:03:46.350 --> 00:03:50.970
and we would do the gauge
fixing without thinking

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:55.440
about any complications,
like these ones,

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:59.620
and these are just involving
ultrasoft fields, so just

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:01.320
QCD, just ultrasoft fields.

00:04:07.270 --> 00:04:07.770
OK?

00:04:07.770 --> 00:04:08.800
So the only place--

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.930
and you take everything
here together--

00:04:10.930 --> 00:04:13.330
the only place that the
ultrasoft and collinear fields

00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:15.370
talk to each other
in the Lagrangian

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:19.490
is in this single component n
dot partial, n dot a ultrasoft.

00:04:19.490 --> 00:04:24.180
And that comes about basically
because of the power counting,

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:26.680
that this is really the only
place that these two things can

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:27.220
interact.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:31.623
And we'll talk about the
implications of that later on,

00:04:31.623 --> 00:04:33.290
but that's the leading
order Lagrangian.

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:36.970
So once you have this piece, and
this piece is pretty straight

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:38.907
forward with this
additional complication

00:04:38.907 --> 00:04:40.990
of worrying about what
gauge symmetry means, which

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:43.392
we'll talk more about later.

00:04:43.392 --> 00:04:45.100
But we had to be
careful not to break it,

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:47.410
when we introduced this
term, because we wanted

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:49.930
to in some sense have a gauge
fixing both for the collinear

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:52.900
gluon and a separate gauge
fixing for the ultrasoft gluon,

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:56.380
and that's why we
wanted to do this.

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:58.130
And then this piece
here is simple.

00:04:58.130 --> 00:05:01.000
It's just QCD, because
it's, if you'd like,

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.710
it's the lowest
energy mode, and it

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:04.690
doesn't know about any
of the complications

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:07.780
that we had for the
collinear modes.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:09.460
OK?

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:11.680
So any questions
about this so far?

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:14.620
OK.

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:17.440
So everything that we did
in deriving these actions

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:19.630
is tree level.

00:05:19.630 --> 00:05:22.120
All the steps that we
did were tree level.

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:24.478
So you can ask, if
I start to do loops,

00:05:24.478 --> 00:05:26.020
will there be some
Wilson coefficient

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:27.580
that shows up somewhere here?

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:29.380
Will I generate
some new operators

00:05:29.380 --> 00:05:31.360
that I don't see here?

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:33.135
Those are reasonable
questions, and that's

00:05:33.135 --> 00:05:34.510
what we're going
to address next.

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:57.870
So to go further,
we'll use symmetries,

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:00.240
and we're actually
going to consider

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.550
three different symmetries,
gauge symmetry, which I've

00:06:02.550 --> 00:06:21.850
been promising you for a while,
reparameterization invariance,

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:23.560
and spin symmetry.

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:32.855
Where I'll put a question
mark by this last one,

00:06:32.855 --> 00:06:35.230
because we need to answer the
question whether there even

00:06:35.230 --> 00:06:37.892
is a spin symmetry.

00:06:37.892 --> 00:06:39.850
These two here, this
number one and number two,

00:06:39.850 --> 00:06:42.970
will turn out to
be quite important.

00:06:42.970 --> 00:06:44.490
Number three is
not so important.

00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:52.110
So reparameterization
invariance here

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:54.510
will be like reparameterization
invariance in HQET,

00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:56.190
except now it's different.

00:06:56.190 --> 00:06:58.530
We've introduced the
parameters and then n bar,

00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:00.660
and we'll have to see
what kind of symmetries

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:05.610
we have with respect to
that choice of basis factors

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:06.893
that we made.

00:07:06.893 --> 00:07:09.060
But it otherwise will be
analogous to our discussion

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:09.585
of HQET.

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:15.730
So let's actually first dispense
with the one that in some sense

00:07:15.730 --> 00:07:18.430
is the least important,
this number three.

00:07:26.460 --> 00:07:31.780
So first, let's revisit
our spinners a little bit.

00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:34.440
So if I put together
the information

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:36.840
that we talked about
when we derived

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:41.340
the equation at the top of the
board there for the Lagrangian,

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:48.360
we worked out at a tree level
we have this formula that

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:49.170
relates the fields.

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.630
So from that formula, if we
just project onto the spinner

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:02.580
pieces, we can
write down a formula

00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:04.680
that relates the spinners.

00:08:04.680 --> 00:08:07.710
So throwing away
the gauge fields,

00:08:07.710 --> 00:08:18.490
we have in momentum space
the u of p, the spinner,

00:08:18.490 --> 00:08:20.050
would be related
to whatever spinner

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:24.640
we have for this cn field which
I call Un by that formula.

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:26.680
And then if you
take this formula,

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:30.250
you also see that if I
hit it with a projector,

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:36.460
n slash n bar slash over 4, if
I hit the u with a projector,

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:37.840
it's going to kill this piece.

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:40.749
Because the n slash n bar slash
can be pushed through the p

00:08:40.749 --> 00:08:45.280
perp slash, then n
bar squared is 0,

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:47.210
so that kills that second piece.

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:49.780
So we also have this formula.

00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:51.700
And then once you
have this formula,

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:57.230
you have the formulas
that we wanted for that.

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:04.600
OK?

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:07.180
But this actually,
this spinner here,

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:09.640
this Un is not exactly
the same as the spinner

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:12.527
that we talked about earlier.

00:09:12.527 --> 00:09:13.360
So let me come back.

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:16.425
Let me come to that in a minute.

00:09:16.425 --> 00:09:17.800
So first thing
you might consider

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:21.640
is whether, when I
take this cn field,

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:24.400
and I take the Lagrangian
up at the top of the board,

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:27.370
do I just get the collinear
propagator that we

00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:28.270
talked about?

00:09:28.270 --> 00:09:29.350
And indeed, you do.

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:38.470
It's kind of obvious for the
momentum-dependent parts,

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:42.470
and really you might only
worry about the spin.

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:45.670
And so if you
consider this formula,

00:09:45.670 --> 00:09:49.480
and you consider the sum
over spins of u u bar which

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:52.000
is what's going to appear in
the numerator of the propagator

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.458
for the Fermion when you're
driving the Fermion propagator,

00:09:54.458 --> 00:09:57.400
you get a sum over
the physical spins.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:01.630
Then, from this formula, this
is a projector on something

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:10.345
you know how to do the spin sum
for which is the full theory

00:10:10.345 --> 00:10:10.845
spinner.

00:10:15.190 --> 00:10:19.120
And that spin sum
is p slash, so this

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:21.550
is like p slash sandwiched
between projectors.

00:10:28.110 --> 00:10:32.610
And you could work out that
that's exactly the numerator

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:38.745
that we had before after a
little bit of Dirac algebra.

00:10:44.150 --> 00:10:46.040
So that part works as expected.

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:48.610
If we take this
Lagrangian, and we work out

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:51.610
what the propagator is, we
get exactly the propagator

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:52.690
we got from expansion.

00:11:13.108 --> 00:11:17.390
So quantizing lc0 gives
us that propagator.

00:11:26.570 --> 00:11:28.970
But the situation is not quite
the same for the spinner.

00:11:39.590 --> 00:11:42.440
And in some sense, this is not--

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:45.110
this point is not
absolutely crucial,

00:11:45.110 --> 00:11:48.830
but actually, there's
a little simplification

00:11:48.830 --> 00:11:51.590
I want to do in order to
discuss the spin symmetry,

00:11:51.590 --> 00:11:54.170
and in order to do
that at this point,

00:11:54.170 --> 00:11:56.585
it's important to
understand this point.

00:11:56.585 --> 00:11:58.460
So that I'm going through
this in some sense,

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:01.593
because then it'll be very easy
to discuss what spin symmetry

00:12:01.593 --> 00:12:02.510
we have in the theory.

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:10.890
So this guy is actually not
equal to our expanded spinner

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:15.990
which putting in
some normalization I

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:21.390
could write like this.

00:12:21.390 --> 00:12:22.920
So this is what we
got by expanding,

00:12:22.920 --> 00:12:25.860
something like this which is
very simple where this u is

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:30.606
equal to 1, 0 or 0, 1.

00:12:30.606 --> 00:12:33.492
in the Dirac representation.

00:12:33.492 --> 00:12:34.950
But that's actually
not what we get

00:12:34.950 --> 00:12:38.970
if we just take the formula
up here and use this.

00:12:43.573 --> 00:12:44.740
So let's see what we do get.

00:13:02.940 --> 00:13:06.830
So if you use the
formula up there,

00:13:06.830 --> 00:13:08.447
then you have the following.

00:13:14.660 --> 00:13:17.020
So here's the full
theory spinner

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:19.391
with a conventional
normalization.

00:13:22.550 --> 00:13:27.790
So this thing and this
thing here is the projector.

00:13:27.790 --> 00:13:30.040
OK?

00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:33.970
So you could work out what that
product is, and it turns out

00:13:33.970 --> 00:13:36.040
that you can write it in
the following way which

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:42.700
is very closely related but
not precisely the same as what

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:44.930
we had before.

00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:49.720
So you can write it in what
looks like the same form

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:56.200
as we have over here, except
this curly U, curly capital U,

00:13:56.200 --> 00:13:57.505
is a more complicated object.

00:14:10.580 --> 00:14:13.070
And it's just whatever I
get by multiplying these two

00:14:13.070 --> 00:14:15.620
things out which turns
out to be something

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:16.790
I can write in that form.

00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:32.260
So it's some
two-component spinner,

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:34.720
but it's got momentum
dependence, unlike our simple

00:14:34.720 --> 00:14:41.690
1, 0 and 0,1.

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:44.133
But everything we said about
Un really depended only

00:14:44.133 --> 00:14:46.550
on the fact that it could be
written in this form in terms

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:48.530
of some two-component spinner--

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:50.540
the fact that n
slash on it was 0,

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:53.990
the fact that it had
projection relation.

00:14:53.990 --> 00:14:59.600
So these formulas here, if
you have a formula like these,

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:02.240
these formulas here are true.

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:04.100
OK?

00:15:04.100 --> 00:15:07.230
So actually, it would be true
whatever spinner we have there.

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:10.640
So why should I want
this U twiddle spinner

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:13.175
and rather than the U spinner?

00:15:17.393 --> 00:15:19.560
That actually has to do
with this reparameterization

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:26.410
invariant, so it'll become
clear when we talk about that.

00:15:26.410 --> 00:15:30.000
But these extra terms
in U relative to those

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:40.120
for the other guy,
the simple U, actually

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:45.162
ensure the proper structure
under reparameterizations.

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:55.317
And basically, it'll
become clear in a moment,

00:15:55.317 --> 00:15:57.400
but basically, if we wanted
to get this U spinner,

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:11.910
we should have a slightly
different projector,

00:16:11.910 --> 00:16:13.610
which I'll call Pn prime.

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:23.390
So we could have used a
different projector which

00:16:23.390 --> 00:16:28.820
is this one, and then
we could have come up

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:31.880
with another projector which
was the Pn bar projector which

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:45.230
would satisfy that the
sum is 1, if we wanted.

00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:49.165
And this projector here, when
acting on the full theory

00:16:49.165 --> 00:16:50.540
field, would have
given something

00:16:50.540 --> 00:16:52.640
that would have
been proportional

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:54.460
to this combination over here.

00:16:54.460 --> 00:16:54.960
OK?

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:55.880
So you just have to believe me.

00:16:55.880 --> 00:16:57.530
I don't want to go
through the algebra,

00:16:57.530 --> 00:16:59.420
or you can check it yourself.

00:16:59.420 --> 00:17:02.810
But this projector here is not
invariant under that symmetry

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:04.165
of reparameterization variance.

00:17:09.310 --> 00:17:11.950
When we talk about
RPI, it'll be clear

00:17:11.950 --> 00:17:17.619
why we want a projector which
is this projector and not

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:20.140
