structure of gauge fields.

00:28:12.610 --> 00:28:15.073
So in order to talk
about U's, we're

00:28:15.073 --> 00:28:16.740
going to want to
divide them into camps.

00:28:16.740 --> 00:28:19.530
And the useful
thing to think about

00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:23.250
is that you want to have
U's that, first of all,

00:28:23.250 --> 00:28:25.170
leave you inside the
effective theory.

00:28:28.290 --> 00:28:30.180
And really what this
means is that you

00:28:30.180 --> 00:28:32.400
want talking about
gauge symmetry

00:28:32.400 --> 00:28:34.230
to commute with your
discussion of talking

00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:37.270
about power counting.

00:28:37.270 --> 00:28:41.040
So by way of
example of this, say

00:28:41.040 --> 00:28:48.350
you had a gauge
transformation that was large,

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:51.590
that made a formula like that
