The momentum of the ultrasoft--

01:05:07.770 --> 01:05:10.610
the ultrasoft momentum
of the collinear

01:05:10.610 --> 01:05:12.700
quark, you pulled
out mv, and then

01:05:12.700 --> 01:05:15.580
the remaining part was
ultrasoft in the discussion

01:05:15.580 --> 01:05:16.780
for this particular thing.

01:05:20.150 --> 01:05:20.710
All right.

01:05:24.650 --> 01:05:26.720
So it's the Wilson
line, the moral of this

01:05:26.720 --> 01:05:29.180
is that what we were doing
before, where we're integrating

01:05:29.180 --> 01:05:31.460
out those collinear
gluons, is actually

01:05:31.460 --> 01:05:32.660
connected to gauge symmetry.

01:05:32.660 --> 01:05:35.180
Because without
that Wilson line,

01:05:35.180 --> 01:05:38.518
we wouldn't have a result
that's invariant under the type

01:05:38.518 --> 01:05:40.310
of gauge symmetry we've
been talking about.

01:05:45.540 --> 01:05:50.120
So this Wilson line carries
these n collinear gluons,

01:05:50.120 --> 01:05:52.910
and those gluons would be the
gluons that in the full theory

01:05:52.910 --> 01:06:01.910
would give you a gauge symmetric
result. They would combine.

01:06:01.910 --> 01:06:04.550
They would be the attachments
to the heavy quark that

01:06:04.550 --> 01:06:06.560
combined with attachments
to the light quark

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:09.878
to give you a result
that's invariant,

01:06:09.878 --> 01:06:11.795
if you looked at word
identities, for example.

01:06:18.100 --> 01:06:20.320
But in the effective
theory, these are just

01:06:20.320 --> 01:06:23.650
put into a Wilson line, because
that's the leading order

01:06:23.650 --> 01:06:26.080
way that they can
show up, but still we

01:06:26.080 --> 01:06:29.680
have a gauge invariant answer.

01:06:29.680 --> 01:06:34.150
So the Wilson line is really
needed for the gauge symmetry.

01:06:34.150 --> 01:06:39.490
And finally, the ultrasofts, as
can be clear from the notation,

01:06:39.490 --> 01:06:41.290
the ultrasofts can
just as well include

01:06:41.290 --> 01:06:46.680
the global transformation,
if you like.

01:06:46.680 --> 01:06:47.930
So we don't really need three.

01:06:47.930 --> 01:06:50.140
We could put the global
back with the ultrasofts.

01:06:57.450 --> 01:06:59.970
Then, we just have two.

01:06:59.970 --> 01:07:01.590
All right.

01:07:01.590 --> 01:07:03.030
So that's our symmetry.

01:07:03.030 --> 01:07:06.000
That's an example
of how it works.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:08.415
Now, let's talk about
covariant derivatives.

01:07:29.710 --> 01:07:32.410
So gauge symmetry ties
together regular derivatives

01:07:32.410 --> 01:07:36.090
with the gauge field, and
here, what it ties together

01:07:36.090 --> 01:07:37.090
at the following things.

01:07:44.630 --> 01:07:46.980
So because of the treatment
of the A ultrasoft

01:07:46.980 --> 01:07:48.980
field as a background,
it actually ties together

01:07:48.980 --> 01:07:49.910
both of these things.

01:08:03.910 --> 01:08:07.750
And then it does what you
expect in a collinear sector.

01:08:07.750 --> 01:08:11.620
It ties together the derivative
with the gauge field.

01:08:15.660 --> 01:08:17.819
And if you're acting
on ultrasoft fields,

01:08:17.819 --> 01:08:20.620
then there's an ultrasoft
covariant derivative

01:08:20.620 --> 01:08:32.510
which is just like that.

01:08:35.920 --> 01:08:37.979
So now, you can ask
the question if I just

01:08:37.979 --> 01:08:39.660
had this gauge
symmetry, which is going

01:08:39.660 --> 01:08:42.038
to force me to use covariant
derivatives-- which I was

01:08:42.038 --> 01:08:43.830
already thinking ahead
to when I wrote down

01:08:43.830 --> 01:08:45.439
the Lagrangian earlier.

01:08:45.439 --> 01:08:45.939
Right?

01:08:45.939 --> 01:08:48.420
We already wrote it in terms
of these kind of objects,

01:08:48.420 --> 01:08:49.878
so it seems like
we're good to go.

01:08:49.878 --> 01:08:51.420
So you can ask the
question if I just

01:08:51.420 --> 01:08:55.080
have power counting,
the cn that we

01:08:55.080 --> 01:08:58.590
decided we're going to use, and
gauge symmetry, is that enough?

01:08:58.590 --> 01:08:59.250
Am I done?

01:08:59.250 --> 01:09:02.053
Do I have everything I need for
the leading order Lagrangian?

01:09:24.760 --> 01:09:29.200
So power counting told us that
we had this type of derivative,

01:09:29.200 --> 01:09:35.810
and that we could have two
of these perp derivatives.

01:09:35.810 --> 01:09:36.310
OK?

01:09:36.310 --> 01:09:38.435
So those are the two type
of terms we were getting.

01:09:44.590 --> 01:09:51.399
There's no other order lambda
squared field structures that

01:09:51.399 --> 01:09:58.100
would have the right dimensions
and that could do the job.

01:09:58.100 --> 01:10:01.580
So these are really the only
two that we have to think about.

01:10:01.580 --> 01:10:03.130
So you could try to
think about maybe

01:10:03.130 --> 01:10:06.880
I can have something with some
additional n bars floating

01:10:06.880 --> 01:10:10.450
around, but really,
it boils down--

01:10:10.450 --> 01:10:12.460
since you need to
get a lambda squared,

01:10:12.460 --> 01:10:15.940
you need either two
perp derivatives.

01:10:15.940 --> 01:10:18.310
You need two of them, because
you still have a rotation

01:10:18.310 --> 01:10:22.690
symmetry around the
direction of motion,

01:10:22.690 --> 01:10:24.970
or you could have an n dot D.

01:10:24.970 --> 01:10:35.110
But there is one operator
that is not rolled out,

01:10:35.110 --> 01:10:40.860
by gauge symmetry alone,
and that is this operator.

01:10:46.470 --> 01:10:53.325
When we wrote the operator, we
had D perp slash D perp slash.

01:10:53.325 --> 01:10:56.370
But nothing stops me from doing
something similar in some way

01:10:56.370 --> 01:11:02.590
by just taking the D perps and
contracting them, like that.

01:11:02.590 --> 01:11:05.290
That's a different operator
than the D perp slash D perp

01:11:05.290 --> 01:11:08.380
operator that we got before.

01:11:08.380 --> 01:11:12.140
Oops, only one of those.

01:11:12.140 --> 01:11:12.640
OK?

01:11:12.640 --> 01:11:14.230
So this operator is
a different operator.

01:11:14.230 --> 01:11:15.640
In a priori, you
could say, well,

01:11:15.640 --> 01:11:17.800
do loop connections
generate this operator which

01:11:17.800 --> 01:11:22.420
is different than the D perp
slash D perp slash operator.

01:11:22.420 --> 01:11:26.743
The answer is no, actually,
but so far what we've done,

01:11:26.743 --> 01:11:27.910
it's not enough to see that.

01:11:38.293 --> 01:11:40.710
So we need actually this other
symmetry that I alluded to,

01:11:40.710 --> 01:11:43.230
the reparameterization
invariance,

01:11:43.230 --> 01:11:45.000
and that will actually
rule out this guy.

01:11:49.370 --> 01:11:51.578
So what's RPI?

01:11:51.578 --> 01:11:53.120
Well, when we
formulated this theory,

01:11:53.120 --> 01:11:55.280
we needed a direction
for the collinear line

01:11:55.280 --> 01:11:57.380
or for the collinear particles.

01:11:57.380 --> 01:11:59.990
And then we needed an
auxiliary vector n bar,

01:11:59.990 --> 01:12:01.550
and we formulated
the whole set up

01:12:01.550 --> 01:12:03.710
in terms of this n and n bar.

01:12:03.710 --> 01:12:06.320
But having vectors like
that that we write down,

01:12:06.320 --> 01:12:09.140
that breaks Lorentz invariance
in the same way that

01:12:09.140 --> 01:12:16.820
specifying v mu in HQET
breaks Lorentz invariance.

01:12:16.820 --> 01:12:19.240
So if you say that m mu
nu is the set of Lorentz

01:12:19.240 --> 01:12:21.760
transformations, the
usual six generators that

01:12:21.760 --> 01:12:26.800
are anti-symmetric, then
the ones that are broken

01:12:26.800 --> 01:12:27.730
are these ones.

01:12:35.550 --> 01:12:44.160
And there's five of them,
and the one that's not broken

01:12:44.160 --> 01:12:49.260
is this one which corresponds
to rotations about the three,

01:12:49.260 --> 01:12:52.110
axis with the axis
specified by n.

01:13:07.210 --> 01:13:07.710
OK?

01:13:07.710 --> 01:13:11.190
So those rotations would act
in the components of these guys

01:13:11.190 --> 01:13:12.840
that are 0, if you like.

01:13:12.840 --> 01:13:14.850
So there's no issue
there, and these guys

01:13:14.850 --> 01:13:17.940
are the guys that are
connected to the pieces that

01:13:17.940 --> 01:13:21.160
were non-0 in general.

01:13:21.160 --> 01:13:23.550
So there's going to be a
larger, because there's

01:13:23.550 --> 01:13:26.580
five things here and
because there's two vectors,

01:13:26.580 --> 01:13:29.250
it's going to be a larger set
of reparameterization symmetries

01:13:29.250 --> 01:13:29.792
than in HQET.

01:13:36.360 --> 01:13:40.120
First, talk about just the
n and n bar themselves.

01:13:40.120 --> 01:13:42.570
There's three types of
reparameterization invariance

01:13:42.570 --> 01:13:48.900
that would leave
n squared equals 0

01:13:48.900 --> 01:13:53.450
and bar squared equals 0
and n dot n bar equals 2.

01:13:53.450 --> 01:13:55.950
And those were the formulas
that we were using over and over

01:13:55.950 --> 01:13:57.210
again really.

01:13:57.210 --> 01:13:59.610
Everything else was
just convention.

01:13:59.610 --> 01:14:01.590
OK?

01:14:01.590 --> 01:14:04.710
So what are those three types?

01:14:04.710 --> 01:14:06.750
Well, we could take
n, and we could

01:14:06.750 --> 01:14:10.290
change it by some amount
in the perp direction

01:14:10.290 --> 01:14:12.690
and leave n bar unchanged.

01:14:12.690 --> 01:14:15.300
And since n bar dot
something perp is 0,

01:14:15.300 --> 01:14:21.900
that would satisfy this, or
we could do the opposite.

01:14:21.900 --> 01:14:23.955
That would be type two.

01:14:23.955 --> 01:14:27.600
So don't change n,
and change n bar.

01:14:30.300 --> 01:14:31.920
And so this is two
transformations

01:14:31.920 --> 01:14:37.020
there's two things specified
by this perp guy and two here.

01:14:37.020 --> 01:14:41.790
And then there's one more
which is called three,

01:14:41.790 --> 01:14:46.450
and this one let me
write it like this.

01:14:46.450 --> 01:14:48.210
It's a simultaneous
transformation

01:14:48.210 --> 01:14:54.960
of these two guys, where I just
do a multiplicative factor.

01:14:54.960 --> 01:14:56.460
Well, a multiplicative
factor is not

01:14:56.460 --> 01:14:59.550
going to change the fact that's
the square of something 0.

01:14:59.550 --> 01:15:02.250
The place where the
normalization comes in

01:15:02.250 --> 01:15:04.470
is this n dot n bar, and
if I just rescale them

01:15:04.470 --> 01:15:09.550
both by an opposite amount, then
that remains satisfied as well.

01:15:09.550 --> 01:15:11.550
So I formulated this in
terms of an infinite--

01:15:11.550 --> 01:15:15.120
I'm going to think about this is
an infinitesimal transformation

01:15:15.120 --> 01:15:18.510
for delta perp, infinitesimal
for epsilon perp.

01:15:18.510 --> 01:15:20.160
I could also expand
this exponential

01:15:20.160 --> 01:15:21.535
and think of it
as infinitesimal,

01:15:21.535 --> 01:15:24.010
but the finite one's easier.

01:15:24.010 --> 01:15:26.850
So let's just think of
the finite transformation

01:15:26.850 --> 01:15:27.540
in the last one.

01:15:30.810 --> 01:15:33.220
Now, this is an
effective theory.

01:15:33.220 --> 01:15:35.220
So whenever we think
about transformations,

01:15:35.220 --> 01:15:36.480
we should think
about power counting.

01:15:36.480 --> 01:15:38.040
We just spent a lot
of time thinking

01:15:38.040 --> 01:15:39.690
about that for gauge
symmetry, and we should think

01:15:39.690 --> 01:15:41.275
about power counting here too.

01:15:41.275 --> 01:15:43.500
Did you have a question?

01:15:43.500 --> 01:15:45.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:46.853 --> 01:15:47.520
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:15:47.520 --> 01:15:53.790
So what I was just about to talk
about, how big things can be.

01:15:53.790 --> 01:15:58.980
So the power counting that's
the right power counting

01:15:58.980 --> 01:16:01.860
for these guys, so these things
are infinitesimal or finite,

01:16:01.860 --> 01:16:04.980
but they also have some counting
in a different space which

01:16:04.980 --> 01:16:08.640
is the power counting space.

01:16:08.640 --> 01:16:13.330
And the right power counting
for these guys is as follows.

01:16:13.330 --> 01:16:16.200
So this means I can
make arbitrarily

01:16:16.200 --> 01:16:19.410
large transformations in a
power counting sense of type

01:16:19.410 --> 01:16:21.000
two and type three.

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:21.990
There's no constraint.

01:16:21.990 --> 01:16:25.650
That's what this means, so that
maybe that's easier to swallow.

01:16:25.650 --> 01:16:28.290
This one, there is a
constraint, and the reason

01:16:28.290 --> 01:16:31.116
that you can think of
there being a constraint,

01:16:31.116 --> 01:16:35.010
I can give you a simple
example, and then you'll

01:16:35.010 --> 01:16:37.580
see how you would derive
the other things as well.

01:16:37.580 --> 01:16:39.735
So think of n dot
P. If you transform

01:16:39.735 --> 01:16:42.180
n dot P, that becomes n dot--

01:16:42.180 --> 01:16:45.120
think of this is n mu, P mu.

01:16:45.120 --> 01:16:49.770
That becomes n mu, P mu
plus delta perp dot P perp.

01:16:52.432 --> 01:16:54.390
So this is order lambda
squared, so this better

01:16:54.390 --> 01:16:55.390
be order lambda squared.

01:16:55.390 --> 01:16:57.310
But this momentum
here is order lambda,

01:16:57.310 --> 01:16:59.602
so you need to have a power
counting for the delta perp

01:16:59.602 --> 01:17:01.890
that makes it of order lambda.

01:17:01.890 --> 01:17:04.625
In order to keep the transform
guy the same size as the guy

01:17:04.625 --> 01:17:06.000
you started with,
because I don't

01:17:06.000 --> 01:17:08.333
want to consider transformations
that would take me away

01:17:08.333 --> 01:17:10.720
from my power counting,
that would violate it.

01:17:10.720 --> 01:17:14.490
So imposing that this thing
is of order lambda squared

01:17:14.490 --> 01:17:15.780
says that this is true.

01:17:15.780 --> 01:17:19.530
If you go through the same
logic for the other guys,

01:17:19.530 --> 01:17:21.750
the n bar component
was order lambda 0,

01:17:21.750 --> 01:17:24.430
so you can make the epsilon
perp of order lambda 0.

01:17:24.430 --> 01:17:28.071
It doesn't cost you anything,
because there's no constraint.

01:17:34.670 --> 01:17:36.590
You're not making something
that would mess up

01:17:36.590 --> 01:17:37.596
the power counting.

01:17:44.550 --> 01:17:47.340
All right.

01:17:47.340 --> 01:17:49.637
So what does this
correspond to physically?

01:17:53.380 --> 01:17:55.660
So type three is
actually pretty simple.

01:17:55.660 --> 01:17:57.460
Type three is like a
boost along-- if you

01:17:57.460 --> 01:17:59.230
think about our
back-to-back vectors,

01:17:59.230 --> 01:18:01.450
type three is like
the analog of a boost,

01:18:01.450 --> 01:18:04.030
but you're transforming
it in the passive sense

01:18:04.030 --> 01:18:05.095
of transforming the axis.

01:18:10.230 --> 01:18:13.380
And what the outcome
is is very simple.

01:18:13.380 --> 01:18:20.130
It just implies that any
operator that has an n

01:18:20.130 --> 01:18:22.360
must have a corresponding
n bar sitting next

01:18:22.360 --> 01:18:27.278
to it, effectively.

01:18:27.278 --> 01:18:28.570
So I'll give you some examples.

01:18:32.070 --> 01:18:33.570
So really, if you have--

01:18:33.570 --> 01:18:36.780
let's just say it this way--
if you have an n bar mu

01:18:36.780 --> 01:18:44.610
in the numerator, then you
either have a corresponding n

01:18:44.610 --> 01:18:51.070
in the numerator, or--

01:18:57.860 --> 01:19:03.390
well, you have an n
bar in the denominator.

01:19:03.390 --> 01:19:06.260
Since we could have n bars
in the denominator and that

01:19:06.260 --> 01:19:07.730
was showing up in some places.

01:19:07.730 --> 01:19:10.040
Those are the two possible
ways of compensating

01:19:10.040 --> 01:19:11.610
for the transformation.

01:19:11.610 --> 01:19:14.610
So it's just like a simple
counting that you have.

01:19:14.610 --> 01:19:24.370
So if you look at our lc
0, we had various terms.

01:19:24.370 --> 01:19:29.462
One of them was n bar slash
1 over i n bar over D.

01:19:29.462 --> 01:19:31.420
So here, we have an n
bar in both the numerator

01:19:31.420 --> 01:19:33.370
and the denominator,
and that compensates

01:19:33.370 --> 01:19:34.840
for the transformation.

01:19:34.840 --> 01:19:40.030
And then in another term, we
had an n bar slash n dot D,

01:19:40.030 --> 01:19:43.425
and then that again is invariant
in this type of transformation.

01:19:50.220 --> 01:19:53.550
What about type one and two?

01:19:53.550 --> 01:19:57.460
So type one is the following.

01:19:57.460 --> 01:20:01.140
So think about these guys
as in this kind of language

01:20:01.140 --> 01:20:03.720
they would be back to back.

01:20:03.720 --> 01:20:05.220
We're trying to
describe the physics

01:20:05.220 --> 01:20:08.310
in this cone for the
collinear particles,

01:20:08.310 --> 01:20:12.360
and n was the vector that was
pointing inside that cone.

01:20:12.360 --> 01:20:15.750
What this is saying, type one,
is that I can rotate that guy,

01:20:15.750 --> 01:20:18.895
and as long as I'm not
rotating it by too much--

01:20:18.895 --> 01:20:19.395
i.e.

01:20:19.395 --> 01:20:21.000
I'm rotating it
by a small amount

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:23.670
of order lambda,
which you can think

01:20:23.670 --> 01:20:25.980
of as staying inside the cone--

01:20:25.980 --> 01:20:27.795
then I can describe
everything equally well

01:20:27.795 --> 01:20:29.670
by some other vector
that lives in that cone,

01:20:29.670 --> 01:20:32.760
and I can decompose the
momenta and the modes

01:20:32.760 --> 01:20:36.820
in terms of that vector, and
it will work equally well.

01:20:36.820 --> 01:20:37.320
OK.

01:20:37.320 --> 01:20:41.050
So that's what type one
is physically doing,

01:20:41.050 --> 01:20:43.260
and so you're not making a
large transformation here,

01:20:43.260 --> 01:20:44.820
because you want to
still be inside the cone.

01:20:44.820 --> 01:20:47.195
You still want something that's
pointing in the collinear

01:20:47.195 --> 01:20:48.030
direction.

01:20:48.030 --> 01:20:51.930
Type two is related to
the fact that this n bar

01:20:51.930 --> 01:20:53.790
vector was just an
auxiliary vector that we

01:20:53.790 --> 01:20:54.838
used to decompose things.

01:20:54.838 --> 01:20:56.130
We didn't really care about it.

01:20:56.130 --> 01:21:03.810
It didn't have a strong
physical motivation.

01:21:03.810 --> 01:21:06.460
It was just needed because we're
using light cone coordinates.

01:21:06.460 --> 01:21:10.485
So I can make a very large
transformation of that guy.

01:21:10.485 --> 01:21:13.942
So here's a large
transformation,

01:21:13.942 --> 01:21:15.150
and I can use some other guy.

01:21:15.150 --> 01:21:17.150
And we gave you an example
earlier, which was 3,

01:21:17.150 --> 01:21:20.670
2, 2, 1 as a possible
value for the n bar,

01:21:20.670 --> 01:21:22.710
and that's something
that you could think

01:21:22.710 --> 01:21:25.620
of getting to by a finite
type two reparameterization

01:21:25.620 --> 01:21:27.520
transformation.

01:21:27.520 --> 01:21:28.020
OK?

01:21:28.020 --> 01:21:32.070
So that's the picture for what
these transformations are,

01:21:32.070 --> 01:21:34.830
and we will finish up
talking about them next time

01:21:34.830 --> 01:21:38.400
and will show that actually this
additional term that we could

01:21:38.400 --> 01:21:40.830
write down in the
Lagrangian is actually

01:21:40.830 --> 01:21:44.660
ruled out reparameterization
symmetries.